## Field-by-field notes

### item_id

Stable identifier. Format: olht- + zero-padded integer. Never reused, never reissued.

### contributors

Multiple people may contribute to a single item (narrator, photographer, translator, etc.). Each gets a row with their own attribution style and consent record. name_public is what is shown; name_internal is the full name held in restricted-access records.

### places

*Coordinate precision matters.* For grave sites, sacred sites, and places vulnerable to extractive interest, set coordinate_precision to redacted_for_protection and either omit the coordinates or generalise them to the nearest island or region.

### local_contexts

The heart of the schema. The toolkit always applies at least one Notice. Labels are added as the community customises them on the Local Contexts Hub. hub_project_uri is generated when the project is registered on the Hub and is what makes the Notices machine-discoverable in DataCite and other systems.

### access.tier

Drives every downstream system. The Memory Constellation Engine, Ask Pulau Brani, and the public Memory Map only see items whose tier permits it. sacred_excluded items are never indexed, never embedded, never retrieved.

### access.ai_processing

A separate axis from access tier. An item might be public to humans but excluded from AI systems (for example, a community might be comfortable with public display but not with paraphrase by a chatbot). Always honour the stricter of the two.

### community_review.confidence

Many items in heritage archives carry uncertainty — names half-remembered, dates approximated, places renamed. Flag this honestly. The CARE Principles call this “preserving uncertainty,” and it matters for downstream AI work because confident-sounding hallucinations are the failure mode to avoid.

### sensitivities

Surface advisory text where culturally needed. Not censorship — context.

### history

Append-only log. Every change is recorded. Withdrawals, re-consents, Label additions, all logged.

-----

## Storage and access

- The full record (including name_internal, consent records, internal notes) is held in a restricted-access store.
- The public-facing surface is a redacted projection of the record, filtered by access.tier.
- AI systems consume a further-filtered projection determined by access.ai_processing.
- All projections carry the Notices and Labels. The Local Contexts framework is meaningless if the protocols are stripped during export.

-----

## Validation rules

1. Every item must have at least one Notice in local_contexts.notices.
1. Every item must have a consent.consent_record_id that resolves to a stored consent record.
1. An item may not be saved with access.tier = "public" if any Label in local_contexts.labels is TK-SS, TK-WR, TK-MR, or TK-CO.
1. An item may not be saved with access.ai_processing = "allowed" if any Label is TK-SS, TK-WR, TK-MR, or TK-CO.
1. If provenance.attribution_incomplete is true, the Attribution-Incomplete Notice must appear in local_contexts.notices.
1. A change to access.tier or local_contexts.labels must append an entry to history.
